Weather Predictor Model -- Using Amazon Forecast to Predict Weather in Basel, Switzerland.¶

Authors: Audrey Bu, Alina Chen, Indy Gu, Alvin Jiao, Yiran Liu¶

Initial Motivation¶

Alvin Jiao: I embarked on a journey to Basel, Switzerland last year to experience its renowned art scene and history. However, this trip turned out to be unexpected. One day, I planned to visit the Fondation Beyeler, a famous art museum in Basel. The weather forecast promised a day of sunshine and clear skies. However, by noon, the weather had taken an unforeseen turn which a sudden downpour and falsh caught me and many other tourists have to change their plans. This abrupt change in weather led to canceled plans and a day spent seeking shelter instead of exploring.

This experience sparked a project idea within our team. Recognizing the impact of unreliable weather forecasts on travel experiences, we aimed to create a solution using advanced forecasting models. Leveraging Amazon Forecast's time-series capabilities, we focused on Basel, analyzing historical data to predict rare weather events accurately. Our goal i to create a more precise forecasting model, poised to revolutionize travel planning, providing travelers like Alvin with better preparedness and flexibility for a seamless travel experience. This project not only bridged the gap between research and application but also offered a practical solution to enhance travel planning worldwide.

Data Collection¶

Upon Alvin's idea, we collected data from the website Meteoblue (https://www.meteoblue.com/en/weather/archive/export). The dataset contains hourly observations of three weather factors: Temperature, Precipitation, and Wind Gust from the year 1960 to 2023. In order to use the data for machine learning, we split it into the training set (80%) and test set (20%) in time series order. In other words, we want to train our model using historical data points and evaluate it using more current ones. We have uploaded all the datasets to a S3 bucket on AWS.

Before doing the machine learning with Amazon Forecast, we want to analyze the dataset a bit to get a general understanding of it.

The temperature plot presents a comprehensive view of hourly temperature data from the 1960s to the 2020s, characterized by pronounced, regular oscillations indicative of seasonal variations. While the plot shows no apparent long-term trend suggesting significant global temperature changes, it maintains a consistent range between the extremes, indicating stable temperature patterns over the decades. The plot's density reflects the hourly data collection frequency, which might obscure finer trends that could be unveiled through data aggregation into larger time units. Occasional sharp spikes suggest potential outliers or rare extreme weather events. Further analysis with statistical tools could clarify underlying trends and isolate seasonal effects from long-term changes.

The histogram provided represents the frequency distribution of temperature data. It's shaped like a bell curve, which closely resembles a normal distribution, suggesting that most temperature readings cluster around the mean, with fewer readings observed as you move towards the extremes. The peak of the distribution appears to be around 50 units, which could be interpreted as the most common temperature range in the dataset. The spread of the data, from near 0 to 100, indicates a wide range of temperatures but with most occurrences around the central value, thus reflecting a typical distribution you might expect from a large set of temperature data. This kind of distribution is beneficial for statistical analysis and predictive modeling since many statistical techniques assume normality. The tails of the distribution taper off, showing that extremely low and high temperatures are relatively rare. This visualization is a key tool for understanding the overall behavior of temperature variation within the dataset.

In the next step of our analysis, we aim to understand how temperature distributions vary with the seasons. To do this, we need to ensure our dataset is indexed by time, allowing us to extract date-related attributes such as the year and month. First, we will convert our date and time information into a DatetimeIndex to facilitate time-based indexing. Once our DataFrame is indexed by datetime, we will extract the 'year' and 'month' from the index, enabling us to categorize our data by these time units. Subsequently, we will map each month to its corresponding season—winter, spring, summer, or autumn. With these new columns in place, we can employ both violin and box plots to visually compare the temperature distributions across different seasons. Violin plots will provide us with a rich depiction of the distribution, showing us both the median and the spread of the data, while box plots will give a summary of the distribution's quartiles and outliers. This visualization will be crucial for interpreting the seasonal effects on temperature.

The violin and box plots provide a visual comparison of temperature distributions across the four seasons. In the violin plot, the width indicates the frequency of temperature readings, revealing a broader spread in temperatures during Spring and Autumn, suggesting more variability in those seasons. Winter shows a tighter distribution at lower temperatures, while Summer exhibits a similar concentration at higher temperatures. All seasons show a roughly symmetrical distribution of temperatures, hinting at a normal-like distribution within each season.

The box plot gives a clear summary of the median, quartiles, and outliers for each season. Winter has the lowest median temperature, while Summer has the highest, which is expected. The interquartile ranges (the boxes themselves) are tightest in Winter and widest in Spring, indicating less variability in Winter temperatures and more in Spring. Outliers are visible in all seasons, particularly in Spring and Autumn, indicating occasional temperatures that are much higher or lower than the typical range. The 'whiskers' of the plot, which indicate the range of typical data points (excluding outliers), are longest in Spring and Autumn, further emphasizing the larger temperature variation in those seasons.

3. Correlation Analysis:¶

Finally, we will perform some auto-correlation analysis and partial auto-correlation analysis to determine the correlation between the temperature values at different time intervals. We use the plot_acf() function to plot the auto-correlation graph and the plot_pacf() function to plot the partial auto-correlation graph. We use plt.show() to display the plot. The auto-correlation graph shows the correlation between the temperature values at different time intervals. The partial auto-correlation graph shows the correlation between the temperature values at different time intervals excluding the correlation due to the intermediate time intervals.

In [20]:
from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_acf, plot_pacf

temperature_df.sort_index(inplace=True)


plot_acf(temperature_df['target_value'], lags=48) 
plt.title('Autocorrelation of Temperature')
plt.xlabel('Lags (hours)')
plt.ylabel('Autocorrelation')
plt.show()

# Perform Partial Autocorrelation Analysis
plot_pacf(temperature_df['target_value'], lags=48)  # 48 lags for 2 days of hourly data
plt.title('Partial Autocorrelation of Temperature')
plt.xlabel('Lags (hours)')
plt.ylabel('Partial Autocorrelation')
plt.show()

/Users/jiaaayiccch/opt/anaconda3/lib/python3.9/site-packages/statsmodels/graphics/tsaplots.py:348: FutureWarning: The default method 'yw' can produce PACF values outside of the [-1,1] interval. After 0.13, the default will change tounadjusted Yule-Walker ('ywm'). You can use this method now by setting method='ywm'.
  warnings.warn(

The autocorrelation plot shows the correlation of the temperature data with itself at various lags, which in this context are hourly time steps. The consistent oscillation with a periodicity of 24 hours (as seen by peaks every 24 lags) suggests a strong daily pattern, likely related to the diurnal cycle of temperatures rising during the day and falling at night. The autocorrelation values are positive and significant for at least the first 24 hours, indicating that past values have a predictive quality for at least one day ahead.

In contrast, the partial autocorrelation plot, which isolates the correlation of each lag without the influence of the intervening lags, shows a significant spike at lag 0 (as expected since it's the correlation with itself) and then drops off quickly. The significant values close to lag 1 and becoming negligible after that suggest that the most recent past value is a strong predictor of the next value, but this predictive power does not persist beyond the immediate past in the time series.

The stark difference between the autocorrelation and partial autocorrelation plots is common in time series data where there is a strong daily pattern. The autocorrelation captures the entire cycle's influence, while the partial autocorrelation shows that once the cycle is accounted for, only the most recent past influences the immediate future. This information is critical when building time series forecasting models, as it suggests incorporating the first lag is likely to be important, and that longer historical sequences may not provide additional predictive benefit.

Drawing from Alvin's travel experiences in Basel and our subsequent data analysis, a compelling story unfolds. The violin and box plots of seasonal temperature distributions correlate with Alvin's recollection of an unexpected chill during his spring visit, demonstrating the season's high variability. Furthermore, the partial autocorrelation findings resonate with the short-term weather forecast's failure on the day of his visit – suggesting that beyond a few hours, predictability falters.

Discussion¶

While our project using Amazon Forecast has demonstrated commendable performance in predicting weather features, particularly temperature, it's crucial to acknowledge certain limitations both within our project and inherent to the Amazon Forecast platform.

First of all, we only ran Amazon Forecast on Temperature instead of all three factors (other two being Precipitation and Wind Gust). This is because running this amount of data takes huge amount of time and needs additional data processing required by Amazon Forecast. The future step is to examine other weather factors, and given its good performance on Temperature, Amazon Forecast is pretty promising.

Secondly, since we used regional weather data, the model's ability to predict weather of regions with greater variations is unknown and need future investigations.

During our interactions with Amazon Forecast, we found several limitations as well.

Firstly, the platform demands meticulous data preprocessing, involving the handling of missing values and the selection of relevant features, which can be intricate and necessitate domain-specific knowledge.

Additionally, achieving optimal model performance often involves time-consuming hyperparameter tuning; while Amazon Forecast provides automated approaches, manual tuning may be necessary for optimal results.

Lastly, the training of complex models on large datasets can be computationally intensive and resource-demanding, potentially posing challenges for users with limited computational capabilities.

These limitations underscore the importance of a nuanced understanding of Amazon Forecast's capabilities and considerations for users in different contexts.
